      "writtenOn": "2017-08-15T20:35:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I researched this a bit more and have a more accurate answer. The same end result continues to apply.\n\nThe C++11 standard [1] specifies in §12.8/7\n\"If the class definition does not explicitly declare a copy constructor, one is declared implicitly. If the class definition declares a move constructor or move assignment operator, the implicitly declared copy constructor is defined as deleted; ...\"\n\nSo simply by specifying the defaulted move ctor/assignment, we effectively delete the copy ctor. I assume this is also true of the copy assignment, but I didn\u0027t actually find mention of that.\n\nHowever, with that said I still believe explicitly deleting makes the code more readable.\n\n[1] http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2012/n3485.pdf",
      "parentUuid": "18f196cb_a54a18ff",
